ch) |page=278  |date=13 December 1958 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref><br>29 January 1959 (substantive)<ref name=\"lt_gen_subs\">{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=115  |date=16 May 1959 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Joyanto Nath Chaudhuri]]\n|title = [[General_officer_commanding#Usage_in_the_Indian_Army|General Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] [[Southern Command (India)|Southern Command]]\n| years = 1963\u20131965\n| after = Moti Sagar\n}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[S. P. P. Thorat]]\n|title = [[General_officer_commanding#Usage_in_the_Indian_Army|General Officer Commanding-in-Chief]] [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]]\n|years = 1961-1963\n|after =[[Paramasiva Prabhakar Kumaramangalam]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Indian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Indian Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of the Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]]\n[[Category:People of the Sino-Indian War]]\n[[Category:Indian generals]]\n[[Category:Indian Army personnel]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Lieutenant-General]]\n|name=Lionel Protip Sen\n| honorific_suffix =[[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]]\n|image=\n|alt=\n|caption= \n|birth_date={{Birth date|df=yes|1910|10|20}}<ref name=\"Indian_Army_List_45\"/>\n|death_date={{Death date and age|df=yes|1981|09|17|1910|10|20}}\n|birth_place=Calcutta, [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br><small>(now [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], India)</small><ref name=\"DSO_cite\"/>\n|death_place= \n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label=\n|nickname=Bogey\n|allegiance={{flag|British India}} (1931-1947) <br />{{flag|India}} (1947-1965)\n|branch={{army|British India}}<br />{{army|India}}\n|serviceyears=1931\u20131965\n|rank= [[File:Lieutenant General of the Indian Army.svg|22px]] [[Lieutenant-General]]\n|servicenumber = AI-77\n| unit = 16/10 [[Baloch Regiment]]<br>[[8th Gorkha Rifles]]\n|commands= GOC-in-C, [[Southern Command (India)|Southern Command]]<br>GOC-in-C, [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]]<br>[[161st Indian Infantry Brigade]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n*[[Burma Campaign]]\n**[[Battle of Hill 170]]\n<br />[[Indo-Pakistan War of 1947]]\n<br />[[Sino-Indian War]]\n|awards=[[Distinguished Service Order]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork= \n|signature= \n}}\n\n[[Lieutenant-General]] '''Lionel Protip \"Bogey\" Sen''' [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] (20 October 1910 \u2013 17 September 1981) was a decorated [[Indian Army]] general. He commanded the [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]] during the [[Sino-Indian War]] of 1962.\n\n==Career==\nA [[King's Commissioned Indian Officer]] (KCIO), Sen attended the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] and was commissioned a second lieutenant in the British Indian Army on 27 August 1931.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33748|supp=|page=5624|date=28 August 1931}}</ref> He was formally appointed to the Indian Army as an officer with the 10th [[Baloch Regiment]] on 26 October 1932 (seniority from 29 January 1931).<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33924|supp=|page=2043|date=24 March 1933}}</ref> He was promoted lieutenant on 29 April 1933,<ref name=\"lt_gazette\"/> and to captain on 29 January 1939.<ref name=\"capt_gazette\"/>\n\nDuring the Second World War, Sen fought in the [[Burma Campaign]] with the 16th Battalion of 10 Baloch. In early 1945, his battalion took a prominent role in the [[Battle of Hill 170]], during which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO).<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37349|supp=y|page=5574|date=13 November 1945}}</ref> The citation recommending Sen for the DSO (which was not published) noted:<ref name=\"DSO_cite\">{{cite web |url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D7370259|title=Recommendation for Award for Sen, Lionel Protip. Rank: Sub Captain, Temporary Major, Acting Lieutenant Colonel |website=The National Archives (UK)|publisher=UK Government |access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> \n\n<blockquote>\n...In spite of the greatest difficulties Lt-Col Sen held firmly on to his precarious positions, and the final success of the whole operation was in no small measure due to his dashing assault and tenacious defence. Throughout, he has proved himself a gallant leader of a gallant Battalion and an inspiration to every officer and man under his command.\n</blockquote>\n\nAs the Baloch Regiment, Sen's parent regiment, was among those regiments allotted to Pakistan following Indian independence, Sen transferred to the 8th Gorkha Rifles. During the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947\u20131948]], he was promoted to acting brigadier and commanded the [[161st Indian Infantry Brigade]], receiving a mention in dispatches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Defence-Press Note|url=http://pibarchive.nic.in/archive/ArchiveSecondPhase/DEFENCE/1948-JAN-JUNE-DEFENCE/PDF/DEF-1948-04-09_208.pdf|website=Press Information Bureau of India - Archive|date=9 April 1948|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> On 16 March 1955, Sen was promoted acting major-general and appointed Director of Military Training (DMT).<ref name=\"maj_gen_actg\"/> He was appointed [[Master-General of the Ordnance (India)|Master-General of the Ordnance]] (MGO) on 8 May 1957,<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=129 |date=25 May 1957 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref> and was further appointed Colonel-Commandant of the Army Physical Training Corps on 26 September.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=280 |date=9 November 1957 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>  \n\nSen was promoted to acting lieutenant-general on 1 August 1958,<ref name=\"lt_gen_actg\"/> and to the substantive rank on 29 January 1959.<ref name=\"lt_gen_subs\"/> On 8 May 1961, he was appointed GOC-in-C, Eastern Command,<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=128  |date=20 May 1961 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref> in which capacity he served during the Sino-Indian War the following year. After the conflict, Sen was appointed GOC-in-C, [[Southern Command (India)|Southern Command]], on 10 May 1963.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=209  |date=22 June 1963 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref> He retired from this posting on 8 May 1965, after nearly 34 years of service.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=306  |date=12 June 1965 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n\nSen died in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indianarmy.nic.in/writereaddata/documents/pensioner/Family_Pensioners%20AI%20EC%20RC%20TC.xls|title=Indian Army - List of Family Pensioners (AI, EC, RC, TC) |date= |website=Indian Army |publisher= |access-date=20 October 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Decorations==\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=India_General_Service_Medal_1947.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Indian_Independence_medal_1947.svg|width=106}}\n|}</center>\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award\u2010star|ribbon=Dso-ribbon.png|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Ribbon_-_1939-45_Star.png|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Ribbon_-_Burma_Star.png|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Ribbon_-_War_Medal.png|width=106}}\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |<center>[[Ge